bar plot by state : north dakota missing

# Create a vector of state classifications
red_states <- c("Alabama", "Alaska", "Arkansas", "Idaho", "Indiana", "Iowa", "Kansas", "Kentucky", "Louisiana", "Mississippi", "Missouri", "Montana", "Nebraska", "North Dakota", "Oklahoma", "South Carolina", "South Dakota", "Tennessee", "Texas", "Utah", "West Virginia", "Wyoming")
blue_states <- c("California", "Connecticut", "Delaware", "Hawaii", "Illinois", "Maine", "Maryland", "Massachusetts", "Minnesota", "New Jersey", "New Mexico", "New York", "Oregon", "Rhode Island", "Vermont", "Virginia", "Washington")
swing_states <- c("Arizona", "Colorado", "Florida", "Georgia", "Michigan", "Nevada", "New Hampshire", "North Carolina", "Ohio", "Pennsylvania", "Wisconsin")

# Load necessary library
library(ggplot2)

# Assuming reduced_survey_data1$inputstate is your data vector

# Count occurrences of each state
state_counts <- table(reduced_survey_data1$inputstate)

# Convert the table to a data frame
state_df <- as.data.frame(state_counts)

# Rename the columns for clarity
colnames(state_df) <- c("State", "Count")

# Update Color column based on state classifications
state_df$Color <- ifelse(state_df$State %in% red_states, "red",
                         ifelse(state_df$State %in% blue_states, "blue",
                                ifelse(state_df$State %in% swing_states, "green", "grey")))

# Create the bar plot with color coding
ggplot(state_df, aes(x = reorder(State, -Count), y = Count, fill = Color)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red" = "red", "blue" = "blue", "green" = "green", "grey" = "grey")) +
  labs(x = "State", y = "Count", title = "Number of Occurrences by State") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability

# Prepare data
data <- reduced_survey_data1 %>%
  mutate(
    pid3 = factor(pid3),
    pid7 = factor(pid7),
    presvote16post = factor(presvote16post),
    presvote20post = factor(presvote20post),
    ideo5 = factor(ideo5),
    gender = factor(gender),
    race = factor(race),
    hispanic = factor(hispanic),
    educ = factor(educ),
    marstat = factor(marstat),
    employ = factor(employ),
    inputstate = factor(inputstate),
    urbanicity2 = factor(urbanicity2),
    Cluster = factor(Cluster)
  ) %>%
  na.omit()

# Split data
set.seed(123)
split <- sample.split(data$Cluster, SplitRatio = 0.7)
train_data <- subset(data, split == TRUE)
test_data <- subset(data, split == FALSE)

# Fit multi-class logistic regression model
logistic_model <- multinom(Cluster ~ ., data = train_data)

predictions <- predict(logistic_model, test_data, type = "class")
conf_matrix <- table(predicted = predictions, actual = test_data$Cluster)
print(conf_matrix)

roc curve

library(pROC)

# Assuming the model predictions are probabilities
prob_predictions <- predict(logistic_model, test_data, type = "probs")

# Convert the true class labels to a binary matrix for ROC calculation
roc_list <- list()
for (class in levels(test_data$Cluster)) {
  roc_list[[class]] <- roc(test_data$Cluster == class, prob_predictions[, class])
}
## Setting levels: control = FALSE, case = TRUE
## Setting direction: controls < cases
## Setting levels: control = FALSE, case = TRUE
## Setting direction: controls < cases
## Setting levels: control = FALSE, case = TRUE
## Setting direction: controls < cases
# Plot ROC curves
plot(roc_list[[1]], col = 1, main = "ROC Curves for Multi-Class Logistic Regression")
for (i in 2:length(roc_list)) {
  lines(roc_list[[i]], col = i)
}
legend("bottomright", legend = levels(test_data$Cluster), col = 1:length(roc_list), lty = 1)
